      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That feeling is very common, but it's important to remember that the math isn't personally targeting you; it's just a standard financial formula designed to spread the cost of borrowing over a long period. The \"cycle\" you feel is simply the natural result of paying interest on a large principal, which is a fundamental concept in finance, not a conspiracy. If you're feeling overwhelmed, it might help to look at your specific amortization schedule to see exactly how much of your payment is going to interest versus principal, which can provide a clearer picture of where your money is actually going.\n\nTo make the principal drop faster, you can try making extra payments toward the principal balance, which will reduce the total interest charged over the life of the loan. Many lenders allow you to make these extra payments without penalty, so it's worth checking with your servicer to see if there are any options to accelerate your payoff. If you're struggling with the payments, you might also consider contacting your lender to discuss refinancing or adjusting your payment plan to something more manageable for your current situation.\n\nIt's completely normal to feel frustrated when the numbers don't add up to what you expect, especially when you're trying to pay off debt quickly. However, understanding",
